segments.text: Well, the Command General of Staff College behind your record says, in your record, said, man, we wish we had more like this General Franklin.
And he was good.
He was good to me.
He was the best active Army General other than General Powell that I could say helped the Reserves.
And I went over and took over command.
And I made some changes there.
Now tell me, yeah, tell me about...
First tell me about this petroleum intersection.
What does that mean?
All these designations, what do they mean?
And this is in 1971?
That's right.
And you were deactivated in 71, then?
Or when?
That's right.
That's right.
That's right.
I had a unit about a year.
You had the unit for about a year.
Yeah, a little more than a year, I guess.
Late 69, 1970, I took over the unit.
And I went up there, and the acting commander
was an administrative assistant named Plunkett, Colonel Plunkett.
He was the acting commander, full colonel.
And he was a civil servant.
We called him administrative assistants.
He was on civil service.
He was paid full-time job for him.
That was his job, livelihood.
And that kind of
brussel me a little bit because I couldn't see a civil servant man being a commander of a unit like that.
No, I mean, it didn't make sense, that's right.
So I went in there, and he was a colonel, and I'm a colonel.
So after I was there for a weekend, a whole week, I was there three days, one Friday, Saturday, and Sunday.
And I had the option.
to either make him my exec officer or declare him excess and put him, remove him from the slot and make him a excess officer.
But he worked full time for the reserve unit.
Now you understand in the reserve unit they have these full time employees.
Well that's what he was.
I asked him to type a letter for me while I was there.
He couldn't type it, didn't know how to type.
And I said to myself, how in the world this guy became a full colonel
administrative assistant who doesn't know how to type.
Then I found out that he really, in my estimation, wasn't capable of being a colonel.
He just wasn't.
So I removed him from my... How did he become?
I don't know.
Well, he and the general before him, I found out later, were really buddies.
So it was a buddy system that got him as far as he got.
And that unit has never passed an IG inspection.
Always busted it.
And so I was told this by the Army commander, a deputy Army commander, and he said, get out there and straighten it out.
And so I did.
I removed him as, yeah, I'm always removing guys.
I removed him as Executive Austin.
I moved up a Lieutenant Colonel John, moved him into the slot.
And I shifted some of the others around.
And next thing I knew, we had an IG inspection and passed it with flying colors.
Another thing, this unit had the highest divorce rate of any Army Reserve unit I know of.
Really?
And you asked, your question is, what's divorce?
Why are you getting the divorces?
Because I was told when I got there by the staff, they said, Colonel, all our people are getting divorces.
and leaving the unit.
I said, well now, what's the problem?
He said, we don't know.
I said, let me look at your schedule.
OK. Terry, they were meeting on a weekend and two Tuesday nights, a month, and two Tuesday nights without pay.
And the whole unit was out there, not the staff.
They weren't at home very much.
So they weren't home at all.
So I said, OK.
At the end of my first meeting, I assembled the whole unit, about 160 people, in this headquarters.
Not counting the outlying units that I had.
I assembled them, and I says, as a new commander, we're not going to have any more weekday meetings.
And we're going to have one weekend a month, and you're going to get paid for all these meetings.
Anytime we have a meeting, you're going to get paid for it.
So you can make your plans now to meet once a month, and it'll be the third weekend of the month.
And when I got through talking, I got the biggest rousing yell I ever heard in my life.
Hey, Friday's your commander.
I mean, recruits, enlisted men doing it.
You know, some of the coming of them.
So I kind of laughed and walked away.
Well, after that, there were no more divorces.
Seriously.
No more, well, except the normal divorces.

but it was because Plunkett had been calling his people out just you know on his own will and then hell the wives and husbands were fighting and so after that it was alright unless it really raised morale oh it really it did it I did a lot of other things too I went around to the sections and visited with them and promoted some people who should have been promoted a long time ago and I and I
Moved people into different rooms, officers, and gave them better accommodations.
And then I went to the Sandia base commander and told him that our accommodations, our facilities were terrible and needed better facilities.
And so we got them.
We went to Alaska for training.
No kidding.
Went up there for two weeks.
And that's where I met General Hollingsworth.
I can't remember right now, Terry, but I had problems with Colonel Pluckett.
See, he was always fighting against me because he was dissatisfied because he didn't get the command.
And so he would try to work against me.
And we got to Alaska.
About the third day, I removed him.
from his job, and I went to see Hollingsworth.
And I said, I need a plane ticket for one of my officers.
I'm sending him home.
And he was a two-star general.
And I told him I need to send him home.
And he laughed.
He says, my goddammit.
You got the money.
You got the ticket.
You can send him home.
But why don't you just sit him on his butt and just let him sit?
Why waste your money in sending him home now?
I said, OK.
I'll do that.
So he says, send him over here, and we'll get him out of your way.
So I did.
I sent him over there.
And Hollingsworth gave me the finest fishing report I ever got in my life.
Really?
He really, he saw me working.
And he just was marveled.
And he was proud that a Texas, an Aggie, would step in and just be as firm and strong and do a job as good as I could do.
And hell, that shaped this unit up more.
The dress was immaculate.
And the military courtesies were just superb.
And I just, you know, I really, and he was so proud.
And he would, he called his staff here, his own people, and presented me to the staff.
He says, I want you to meet the finest damn commander that I've ever, yeah, that I've ever met.
And he said, look, he's got the Silver Star and the Purple Heart, and he was a forward observer in the Bulge, and he's back home alive.
He says, we're so proud of him, and, and, uh.
When we left, we had a banquet and invited he and all his staff.
That guy was just, he just praised.
We ran the pipeline.
I forgot to tell you.
What we'd do, we'd unload the oil.
Yeah, what is it, a petrol intersection on Manhattan?
That's right.
Let's get to that.
The Army has a pipeline in Alaska, 600 miles.
No kidding.
Not one drop of oil has ever been spilled.
You know how they talk about the environment, you know, they're all...
Well, that's tremendous.
They would come into a little town.
A ship would come into Alaska, unload it, put it in the tanks.
Then we'd go to the tank, and we'd put it in the pipeline and take it up to Fairbanks, Alaska, and to the distribution point.
And we ran the oil up there.
And we monitored the pipeline and kept the oil going.
Hollingsworth, General Hollingsworth, would give all the people who ran the pipeline, and they were civil servants, give them all vacations while we come up here and run the pipeline for them.
Oh, yeah.
We would perform a good service for them.
And so all along the pipeline, they had little stations, and people, three or four, a family would live at a station.
Maybe two families or three families lived at these pumping stations.
I would take my chaplain, and they never thought about it before.
I said, now, chaplain?
He asked me when he got there, he said, what am I going to do, Colonel?
I said, chaplain, I want you to get your jeep, and I want you to go up to Fairbanks, 600 miles away.
And the two weeks you're here, I want you to go down the pipeline and conduct services for all those people.
And a lot of them hadn't seen a priest or preacher in months, and he did.
And he conducted services for all the people along the pipeline.
That's a great idea.
Oh, it's real hollingsworth to Dad.
He couldn't believe it.
And the people along the pipeline just loved it.
Yes, you know.
And they would spend a day or two with him.
You know, they wouldn't just come in for an hour or two and go.
They would stay a day and conduct regular Bible lessons with him, conduct services, whatever denomination they were.
Some of them.
I think he told me he ran across a couple of Greek Orthodox.
I said, what, did you do your cross the right way?
You know, the Grand Catholic and Greek Orthodox are different crosses.
But anyway, and Hollingsworth just loved it.
Anyway, we left, and he praised us and told us, you know, we've got lots of good places.
Why were you only there in this unit for a year?
They deactivated the unit.
Department of the Army said they didn't need it in their inventory anymore.
So they deactivated it, and instead of a general slot, general position, they made it a full colonel slot.
So were you sort of out of a job then?
I was kind of dangling, because my name had been presented to the Senate for promotion to general.
In other words, you were still a colonel.
I was still a colonel.
You were in sort of, I see.
Yeah, I was still a colonel, but my name
Had to go to the Senate and then to the president to be okay.
And of course, before you become a general, it goes through all kinds of boards.
Fifth Army Board and then TRADOC training division, training command.
Not TRADOC, CONARC, Continental Army Commander.
Go through there and then
And you're in competition with others for the same job.
So they have to send in three colonels for a Brigadier General slot.
And so finally I got selected.
The Department of the Army selected me to be, they called me Brigadier General Designee.
And that was a big step.
Once I got that step, then I had the title, Brigadier General Designee, which I could occupy any general slot.
Then the Department of the Army came out and said, we're going to deactivate the unit.
We don't need it anymore.
What did you think of that time?
I was sick.
I bet you that meant you probably thought that you would stay current.
Yeah, I was, you know, what am I going to do?
Well, I got a call from General Franklin.
He says, come see me.
So I went to see him.
He says, now, Mike, we're very, let me show you what he said.
very much extremely, he kind of got me, very much extremely pleased with your performance.
You are a general officer material, and we're going to give you a general officer slot.
I said, don't you worry.
You've got a general officer slot.
I said, fine.
He says, now there's three openings.
the Engineer Brigade in Bryan, Texas, a Brigadier General slot at the 75th Maneuver Area Command.
So we're getting back to General Davis now.
And we're going to activate a deputy commander slot with the 90th ARCOM, 90th Army Reserve Command.
It's a reserve command headquarters.
that controlled lots of reserve units, 35, 40 units, small units.
Now he says there's three of them.
Located in this area?
San Antonio, Texas.
Located in Fort Sam Houston.
Now the engineer brigades at Bryan and the other ones at Yale.
So he says, which one would you like to have?
Really?
That's fantastic.
This guy, this General Franklin, he says,
And he really makes you feel good.
You don't know how.
Which one would you like to have?
What would you want?
Which job would you like to have?
That's fantastic advice.
It really gets you.
Why did you decide on the 90th?
The Army of Command.
And why did you decide as the deputy instead of the commanding officer in two other positions?
Right.
That went through my mind.
And the 90th command slot kind of appealed to me because General Travis was the commander.
So I knew in a couple years he would retire and then I could step up.
That's the normal procedure.
And if I went to the 75th Command, I would be with General Davis.
And you know, he didn't, wasn't too crazy about it because he had his own men over there.
And Hayden, and Concordall, and they were all buddy-bud.
And then, Bryan, Texas, Engineer Brigade.
You didn't have much experience.
I didn't have any experience in engineering.
I wasn't an engineer.
And I said, well, I'll just take the...
So I told Jennifer, I said, I'll take the San Antonio job.
He says, oh, I forgot to tell you.
He says, General Travis is going to retire, and we're going to take Brigadier General Warren Myers, who I knew very well, and bring him out of control group and make him the commander.
I said, okay, fine, I know Warren well.
We served together 9th Division, Oklahoma.
And I said, oh sure.
So I took over the 90th, so I was assigned the 90th Deputy Commander slot.
And Myers was a commander, and we both went in as Brigadier Generals, and both went in at the same time.
And at the first, we were good friends.
And we stayed friends.
Except he hadn't been with troops for five, six years.
And he didn't know how to really command the 90th.
And he relied on my judgment and my advice to command it, which is fine.
He had his office, and I had my little office.
And we worked very well.
A lot of things he did, I didn't particularly thought it was a proper thing to do.
But anyway, he was the commander.
And so I went along with him.
And he would ask me different advice, and I'd give it to him, and he would accept it.
But then it got to a point, Terry, where he played a lot of politics.
Really upset me.
In what sense?
Well, he began to move staff around and wasn't capable.
He wasn't a strong commander at all.
We had some people in the civil servant positions that we should have got rid of a long time ago, and he wouldn't do it.
And since he lived in San Antonio and they lived in San Antonio, they became buddy-buddy.
He buddy-bud too much with his staff, the lower echelon staff.
And even some of the listed men.
But anyway, that didn't deter my determination to do a good job.
I went to San Antonio every Monday for four years.
Never missed a Monday.
I would go Monday at noon and drill Monday night and come back Tuesday noon.
Drive all the way.
And I told General Myers, I said, General Myers, everybody that I know of,
is going to weekend drills.
I said, no, I think we ought to go to, I think we can get more out of it.
I says, I don't mind driving back and forth, but I think the weekend drill, multiple drill, we called them in, would mute us, would be the thing for us to do.
And no, sir, he wouldn't do it.
Well, about that time, after about a year,
When I took over, we had a big drug problem throughout the Regner Army.
And so the reserve began to get active in the drug problem.
So he asked me to be the drug officer and set up a plan for the 90th Army Reserve Command.
And we had about 26 units then.
They eliminated some units, and we wound up about 26 units.
And we had approximately how many men?
5,000 reservists.
Reservists.
All scattered all over Texas and New Mexico and up in Sweetport, Louisiana.
Anyway, I became the drug and alcohol abuse officer for the 90th Archive.
So they sent me to school at the University of Oklahoma.
It was a 10-day school.
And I was the ranking officer in the class.
By that time, I got promoted to Brigadier General.
So he got promoted to two stars, and I was one star.
And then this schooling was not only Reservists or National, but Active Army people, about 60 of us.
When I came back, I organized a plan for the 9th ARCOM that was the model plan
for all the reserve units in the United States.
No kidding?
Tell me about that plan.
Well, I emphasized physical fitness programs for the people and the reserves.
They had people coming from all over the reserve from the commands from all over the United States to come look at our plan and see what we had.
And the Army commander commended me for it.
Myers has yet to commend me for it.
Then I began to sense a little jealousy there, right after that.
And what else besides physical fitness?
Well, we had, instead of the medical doctors coming in and talking, I asked for psychiatrists to come in and talk.
It was that type of program.
And we had rap sessions among the people who were indulged in using dope, marijuana especially.
And all the units, we sent it down to all the units.
Well, the main thing I think they recognized, we began to tell them about the dope problem, you know, and alcohol.
We had classes, we had lectures.
And I would visit with them, you know, and the emphasis came down from the top, strong.
And believe it or not, we did not have a problem.
We didn't have any kind of problem in the reserve program.
Except in Albuquerque.
After I left, Plunkett became the commander.
General Myers put him in there.
Then they had a load.
that had a little dope problem about a year later.
And then we had the plan and we cleared all that up.
The alcohol, it wasn't prevalent.
There wasn't no problem in the reserve.
Prior to that, these are secrets, shall I tell you secrets?
Yeah.
We know how to get rid of them on the tape when you read it.
I don't know.
Let me tell you something.
Well, General Myers.
You don't have to tell me anything about the personnel, but tell me about the Army.
Well, General Myers told me, he said, General Travis stepped aside two years from retirement to let him take over, and when it came time for me to be promoted, he would step aside.
But he never did.
Which I didn't ask for it.
I didn't care if he would step aside or not, you know.
didn't make me any difference.
But Myers disappointed me as one of the, he's one of the generals that really disappointed me in his performance.
Well, how'd you get out of there?
Okay, I stayed there.
As the deputy, and how did you go to the commander of the 75th?
Okay, after about four years in the 9th ARCOM, General
The Deputy Army Commander, General Rutan, we became friends.
Because I used to come, I used to go to Fort Sam and go down to the track and gym and work out before I went to the meetings.
And he found out I was a handball player and wanted to play handball, so we played handball and then racquetball.
Actually, we became friends.
There was an opening that came up in the 75th Mac.
General Davis was retiring.
And he wanted to know if I wanted to move down there.
And I said, yes, I would.
So I moved into the 75th MAC.
And when I did, they reorganized the MAC and split it up into three units, command headquarters, and then combat support, no, combat service support, and combat arms.
I took over as commander of the combat arms division.
and I went in and reorganized the structure and was commander two years and I retired there at 75th and Mack.
Was that, would you consider that as far as your reserve career the highlight of your career?
Or what would you consider the highlight of your career as far as a reserve officer?
I would, yeah, I think that was a highlight of my career because I went to the 75th MAC as a general officer.
It's the first time that any outsider of the 75th MAC became a general officer.
There's always, in the 75th MAC, they were inbred.
And I went over there with resistance from the commander
and the other general officer.
Was the commander a two-star?
Yes.
Of course, they wanted to promote their own.
I can understand that.
But that was one of the reasons why General Rutan asked me to go down there is because there was too much inbreeding going on and the unit was low.
It was bad, bad shape.
And they wanted to reorganize it.
And he wanted me to
to being part of it.
And of course, I was about ready then, because I was tired of going back and forth saying I'm used to it.
And I couldn't see if it was once a month would be OK.
So I went down there.
And for about three or four months, it wasn't an easy job, Terry, even as a general officer.
What were the problems?
A lot of resistance?
Well, a lot of resistance and a lot of cliques and here I come from the outside.
Even though everybody knew me.
I'm sure you'd been there before.
I'd been there before and my record, I mean, you know, throughout Fifth Army area everybody knew what I had done in Albuquerque and what I'd done at Fort Sam Houston.
So everybody knew me but

I reorganized the combat arms division of the 75th MAC, and the active army advisor, Colonel Spencer, was just, he couldn't believe the accomplishment of what I was doing in comparison to the combat service support side.
So he could compare, and we were head and shoulders above it.
And my deputy, Harry Conrad, is now a Brigadier General in the MAC.
And I recommended him to the job.
Over six colonels who outranked him and who'd been there longer than he has.
And Army bought my recommendation.
So he'll be, I guess he'll be the eventual commander in another year over there.
But that was a good duty.
I went to the field a lot, to Fort Lewis, Washington, Camp DeBispo in California, Wisconsin, Fort McCoy.
Traveled all over the United States putting on these maneuvers and exercises.
was got the Legion of Merit for doing it.
Really?
Yeah.
Did you expect that?
No, I didn't expect it.
The Army gave it to me.
They gave it to me when I retired two years and said because of my work in the Maneuver Area Command.
Oh yeah, I look back over at the
Ninth ARCOM?
I was sort of an advisor to all the people in the reserve.
They all come to me with their problems and everything, the colonels and lieutenant colonels.
And one of them in particular was chief of staff named Bob Lane.
He was a full colonel.
And he came to me and he says, General Kokonos, I'm going to transfer out and go to a direct support group that was meeting in New Brunswick.
I said, what are you going to do over there?
He said, I'm going to be the deputy, and they told me I could take over the command later on.
I said, well, Bob, let me tell you what you do.
You stay right here.
Don't you move out.
Why?
He said, well, you may become one of the generals in this, because I'm going to retire, and so is General Miles.
Oh, no, no, I need to go over and get command experience.
Well, he was right.
He hadn't had any command experience.
But anyway, he said, okay, I'll listen to you.
I'll stay.
So he stayed.
He's now a two-star general commanding the 9th Air Command.
Oh, really?
Yeah.
Yeah.
And I feel like that I was part of him getting that job.
Oh, yeah.
If he'd have moved out, he would have never been made general.
There was no way he could get general.
Because you have to be in the command channel or in a command channel.

leading to the chop i did it the hard way i did it the hard way in what sense in sense that i well uh i was never in a unit that had general officers where i could work myself up except in the ninth division and that was disbanding then after that i was strange stranger to all these units like the 75th maneuver command direct support group that was a brigadier general slot
over in New Orleans.
But going to the Army War College, I went to the Army War College.
I want to go to those service schools.
Let's talk about those.
1970, graduated in the first non-resident U.S. Army War College.
What does it mean, non-resident?
Non-resident is correspondent course.
Oh, okay.
For two years.
It's a two-year course.
Correspondent course.
And in the summertime, we'd go to a two-week school at Carlisle Barracks at the War College.
We did the first summer and we did the second summer.
We graduated.
We were the first non-resident course that they put on.
Up to that time, as a reservist or National Guardsman, you had two slots open in the regular course.
And if you wanted to go to the
work college you had to apply for those two slots and if you out of a hundred people who applied you had no chance.
So they tried this and sixty percent of us were reservists and forty percent were active army people, regular army people in this car spot, yeah.
So this just wasn't for the reservists?
No, it wasn't for the reservists.
And it equaled to the
If you got a degree in a non-resident course, it was the same as getting a degree, a diploma, in the regular resident course.
So the merit was the same for promotion to general.
And that was Paramount and their active army to be general, to go to the War College.
They had to go to the War College.
They had to go to the War College.
And the reserve, they wanted to make it Paramount, too.
That's why they set it up.
But there's a lot of politics in the reserve.
A lot of guys didn't go to the War College, got more general.
But after we completed that two year course, they realized that we had a double dose of it.
We took twice as much classes as the regular Army course did.
So they cut it down.
They cut down the lessons.
My thesis was, we had to write a thesis.
Really?
Yeah, god dang.
My thesis was on the storage of oil in the middle of the ocean.
You know how you got these oil fields, these wells out there now?

I'd contend and instead of trying to build pipelines all the way in, get rubber bags and fill them full of oil and then a ship would come up, press a button and a snorkel would come up and hook up and
take the oil out and then carry it in.
Or if the battleships, the Navy needed oil, they'd press a button, the snorkel would come up.
I'll give it to you in a simple term, but I went out here to Bethlehem Steel, who builds these rigs, and I got all kinds of oil books and sat down and researched it and got a pretty good paper.
Pretty neat.
They said, Terry, that the course we took was
master's degree level.
Great.
It was that way.
You ask Catherine, on Saturday nights, instead of going out, I was at the dining room table doing my lessons for the War College.
Oh, yeah.
I spent many hours doing it, and it was tough.
Tough.
Now, you've got to remember, I was 1970.
You hadn't been to school for a while.
Oh, yeah.
I was 50 years old.
But I enjoyed it.
It was good.
It was challenging, you know.
Catherine would come in and we'd discuss the communist parties in different countries, you know, and that's what most of it was about.
And when we got to college, the War College, we actually drew up the budget for the Army, Department of the Army.
The actual budget.
How many tanks we needed, how many guns we needed, how many trucks we needed.
Of course, we had a format to follow.
And it was very good.
But I was glad to see that they gave it.
Hollingsworth, there's what they call a Hollingsworth Report.
I keep bringing his name up because he was a very prominent officer.
They had a Hollingsworth Report.
He headed up a team, a blue chip team, back in 1965 that outlined the steps for a reserve officer to become general.
And that was Command, Command General Staff College, and the Army War College.
And I took every one of those steps.
And I think that had a lot to do with it.
How about the General Staff College?
Command General Staff at Fort Laverne?
Very fine school.
Tell me about that.
It dealt with tactics.
You were there in 1961, yeah?
Yeah, it dealt with tactics.
I went there, and I was at the resident, of course.
And I look back now, and I don't know how Catherine let me go.
How long was it?
From January to May.
No kidding.
Yeah.
She came up a couple of times and stayed with me.
But we had four kids, yeah, four kids.

I'll tell you right here, I don't care what they say, a career reservist, and I was a career reservist, I could never accomplish being a general officer unless I had a dedicated wife who really sacrificed
her time for me to be gone like I was.
Yeah, five months?
Oh, yeah.
Not only that, but on weekends.
And at nights, and I don't see, yeah, she's still with me.
I couldn't have ever done it, and Catherine has been a big asset to me.
Not only in that, but socials, we go to socials, you know, receptions and stuff, see-saw.
She's an extrovert.
Just people love her.
And so I never could accomplish what I did without her.
No question about it.
Well, just the dedication of you going out and leaving your job, your profession, for five months to take this.
What was going on back at the store?
Yeah, well, of course, I called about every other day and checked and made decisions from there.
And came home.
one time during Easter and did a lot of work.
But it was pretty well taken care of.
But Command General Staff College taught you tactics on how to maneuver.
It was just fine school, college.
I won the school handball championship while I was there.
That's a story.
I went down there.
First Sunday I got there, I went and took my gloves.
And I was tired from traveling and everything.
I went down to the handball courts to play.
And two guys were playing.
And I asked them to play cut-throat with me.
They said, oh, no, we want to play singles.
So I said, OK.
I introduced myself then.
One was named Adler.
And I think the other guy was named Hanson.
But Adler, then as I walked out the door, there was a sign-up scheduled for a tournament, a school tournament.
So I signed up.
Adler and I met in the finals, Major Adler.
And I just beat the hell out of him.
And he says, why did you beat me so bad?
Because you wouldn't let me play cut throw with you, wouldn't I?
Oh, you were the little fellow that come down and won the play.
I said, that was me.
